===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|treden}}, from {{inh|en|ang|tredan}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*tredan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*trudaną}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|treads|treading|trod|past2=tread|past3=treaded|trod|past_ptc2=tread|past_ptc3=trodden|past_ptc4=treaded}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[step]] or [[walk]] (on or over something); to [[trample]].
#: ''He '''trod''' back and forth wearily.''
#: ''Don't '''tread''' on the lawn.''
#* {{RQ:Authorized Version|Joshua|14|9|passage=And Moses sware on that day, saying, Surely the land whereon thy feet haue '''troden''', shall be thine inheritance, and thy childrens for euer, because thou hast wholly followed the Lord my God.}}
#* '''1711''', [[w:Alexander Pope|Alexander Pope]], ''[[w:An Essay on Criticism|An Essay on Criticism]]'', Part III:
#*: Fools rush in where angels fear to '''tread'''.
#* '''1667''', {{w|John Milton}}, ''Paradise Lost''
#*: yee that walk The Earth, and stately '''tread''', or lowly creep
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[step]] or [[walk]] upon.
#: ''Actors '''tread''' the boards.''
# To beat or press with the feet.
#: ''to '''tread''' a path; to '''tread''' land when too light; a well-'''trodden''' path''
# To go through or accomplish by walking, dancing, etc.
#* {{rfdatek|en|Beaumont and Fletcher|and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url, full name of author}}
#*: I am resolved to forsake Malta, '''tread''' a pilgrimage to fair Jerusalem.
#* {{rfdatek|en|Shakespeare|and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url}}
#*: They have measured many a mile, / To '''tread''' a measure with you on this grass.
# To [[crush]] under the foot; to [[trample]] in contempt or hatred; to subdue.
#* {{rfdatek|en|Bible}}, Psalms xliv. 5
#*: Through thy name will we '''tread''' them under that rise up against us.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[copulate]]; said of (especially [[male]]) [[bird]]s.
#: {{rfquotek|en|Shakespeare}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|of a male bird}} To copulate with.
#: {{rfquotek|en|Chaucer}}

=====Usage notes=====
* {{m|en||Treaded}} is not commonly used in the UK and is less common in the US as well. It is apparently used more often in {{m|en|tread water}}.
* {{m|en||Tread}} is sometimes used as a past and past participle, especially in the US.

