[[File:Stairway Measurements.svg|thumb|right|diagram of a set of steps showing the '''tread''']]
{{en-noun}}

# A step taken with the foot.
# A manner of stepping.
#* {{rfdate|en|and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url, full name of author}} {{w|Tennyson}}
#*: She is coming, my own, my sweet; / Were it ever so airy a '''tread''', / My heart would hear her and beat.
# The sound made when someone or something is [[walk]]ing.
#* '''1886''', {{w|Robert Louis Stevenson}}, {{w|Strange Case Of Dr Jekyll And Mr Hyde}}
#*: The steps fell lightly and oddly, with a certain swing, for all they went so slowly; it was different indeed from the heavy creaking '''tread''' of Henry Jekyll. Utterson sighed. "Is there never anything else?" he asked.
#* '''1896''', {{w|Bret Harte}}, Barker's Luck and Other Stories
#*: But when, after a singularly heavy '''tread''' and the jingle of spurs on the platform, the door flew open to the newcomer, he seemed a realization of our worst expectations.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[way]]; a [[track]] or [[path]].
#: {{rfquotek|en|Shakespeare}}
# The horizontal part of a step in a flight of stairs.
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1956|year_published=1972|author=Anthony Burgess|authorlink=Anthony Burgess|title=Time for a Tiger|series=The Malayan Trilogy|page=25|passage=The dog was waiting for him, her paws on the second '''tread''', pere regardant with a happy lolling tongue.}}
# The [[grooves]] carved into the face of a [[tire]], used to give the tire [[traction]]. {{defdate|from 1900s}}
# The [[grooves]] on the bottom of a [[shoe]] or other footwear, used to give grip or traction.
# {{lb|en|biology}} The [[chalaza]] of a bird's egg; the [[treadle]].
# The act of [[avian]] [[copulation]] in which the male [[bird]] [[mount]]s the female by standing on her back.
# {{lb|en|fortification}} The top of the [[banquette]], on which soldiers stand to [[fire]] over the [[parapet]].
# A [[bruise]] or [[abrasion]] produced on the foot or ankle of a [[horse]] that [[interfere]]s, or strikes its feet together.

